clear all;
%%
%[text] ## Problem 1. Dimensional analysis: oscillating Stokes layer
%[text] ### Background
%[text] The Stokes oscillating layer (or oscillatory boundary layer) describes the thin layer of viscous fluid near a surface that moves back and forth due to oscillatory motion, such as a large flat plate oscillating siunusoidally in its own plane with a given velocity, $U(t)$. Ref figure.
%[text] Where $U(t) = U\_0cos(\\omega t)$
imshow("Stokes oscillatory boundary layer diagram.21JAN2026.png")
%[text] **Exponential Decay:** The fluid velocity oscillates with the same frequency as the wall, but its amplitude decays exponentially as distance from the wall increases. \[1\]
%%
%[text] ### Applications
%[text] #### Heat Transfer Enhancement
%[text] Compact heat exchangers need effective mixing, which occurs when the oscillation frequency is tuned so $\\delta$ matches the thermal diffusion length. \[2\]
%[text] #### Vibration-Induced Drag & Noise
%[text] Used in early-stage aeroelastic modeling to estimate viscous energy losses. The Stokes layer determines aerodynamic damping, noise generation, and flutter stability. \[3\]
%%
%[text] ### Analysis
%[text] Assumptions:
%[text] - Flow is laminar and two dimensional
%[text] - Compressibility and gravity is neglected \
%[text] The characteristic thickness $\\delta$ of the oscillatory boundary layer is the distance from the wall where the velocity amplitude has decayed to 1/*e* of its wall value.
%[text] #### 1. Dimensional analysis for $\\delta$
%[text] Using the Buckingham- $\\prod$ theorem --
%[text] <u>Step 1</u>
%[text] List parameter in functional form:
%[text] $\\delta = f(\\omega, \\rho, \\mu)$
%[text] this functional relationship posits the idea that the boundary layer thickness (dependent variable) is a function of independent variables: angular frequency, and the fluid's density and viscosity.
%[text] $n = 4$ (four total parameters)
%%
%[text] <u>Step 2</u>
%[text] **Primary dimensions**
%[text] - $\\delta: \[L^1\]$
%[text] - $\\omega: \[T^-1\]$
%[text] - $\\rho: \[M^{1}L^{-3}\]$
%[text] - $\\mu: \[M^1L^{-1}T^{-1}\]$ \
%[text] $\\rightarrow$ 3 primary dimensions
%%
%[text] <u>Step 3</u>
%[text] Set the reduction *j* as the number of primary dimensions (initial guess)
%[text] Reduction: $j = 3$
%[text] If correct, number of $\\prod$'s: $k = n - j = 4 - 3 = 1$
%%
%[text] <u>Step 4</u>
%[text] Choose *j* repeating parameters.
%[text] Repeating parameters: $\\omega, \\rho, \\mu$
%[text] - Note: Following the guidelines for picking repeating parameters, we cannot pick the dependent variable $\\delta$ \
%%
%[text] <u>Step 5</u>
%[text] Construct *k* $\\Pi$'s, manipulate as necessary.
%[text] The dependent $\\Pi\_1$ is generated by assuming a dimensionless product:
%[text] $\\Pi\_{1} = \\delta \\omega^a \\rho^b \\mu^c$
%[text] Force $\\Pi\_1$ to be dimensionless by setting the exponent of each primary dimension to zero. Then determine the constant exponents by equating the exponents of each primary dimension:
%% Buckingham Pi via Symbolic Math Toolbox
% Variables: delta, omega, rho, mu
% Dimensions (M, L, T):
%   delta : L^1
%   omega : T^-1
%   rho   : M^1 L^-3
%   mu    : M^1 L^-1 T^-1

clear; clc;

syms a b c real           % unknown exponents for omega, rho, mu
syms delta omega rho mu    % symbols for readability (not strictly needed)

% Dimension exponents for each variable in [M L T] order
% Rows correspond to variables: [delta; omega; rho; mu]
D = [ 0  1  0;   % delta
      0  0 -1;   % omega
      1 -3  0;   % rho
      1 -1 -1];  % mu

% Build the dimension balance for Pi = delta^1 * omega^a * rho^b * mu^c
% Total exponents in [M L T] must be zero:
%   1*D(delta,:) + a*D(omega,:) + b*D(rho,:) + c*D(mu,:) = [0 0 0]
eqM = D(1,1) + a*D(2,1) + b*D(3,1) + c*D(4,1) == 0;
eqL = D(1,2) + a*D(2,2) + b*D(3,2) + c*D(4,2) == 0;
eqT = D(1,3) + a*D(2,3) + b*D(3,3) + c*D(4,3) == 0;

sol = solve([eqM, eqL, eqT], [a, b, c], 'ReturnConditions', true);

a_sol = simplify(sol.a);
b_sol = simplify(sol.b);
c_sol = simplify(sol.c);

fprintf('Solved exponents:\n');
fprintf('a = %s\n', string(a_sol));
fprintf('b = %s\n', string(b_sol));
fprintf('c = %s\n', string(c_sol));

% Construct the Pi group
Pi = simplify(delta * omega^a_sol * rho^b_sol * mu^c_sol);
disp('Buckingham-Pi group Pi =');
pretty(Pi)

% Optional: express Pi in a nicer combined form
Pi_nice = simplify(delta * sqrt(omega*rho/mu));
disp('Equivalent simplified form:');
pretty(Pi_nice)
%%
%[text] (a) Thus, the only minimal independent group is:
%[text] $\\Pi\_1 = \\delta \\left( \\frac{\\omega \\rho}{\\mu} \\right)^{1/2}$
%%
%[text] <u>Step 6</u>
%[text] (b) Re-writing the result in the form:
%[text] $\\frac{\\delta}{\\L\_{\*}} = \\Phi(\\Pi)$
%% Dimensional analysis – Part (2)
% Writing the result as delta / L* = Phi(Pi)

clear; clc;

syms delta omega nu real positive

% Define characteristic length scale
Lstar = sqrt(nu/omega);

% Define the Buckingham Pi group
Pi = simplify(delta / Lstar);

disp('Characteristic length scale L* =');
pretty(Lstar)

disp('Buckingham Pi group Pi = delta / L* =');
pretty(Pi)

% Express the dimensional-analysis result symbolically
Phi = sym('C');   % unknown O(1) constant from dimensional analysis
delta_result = simplify(Phi * Lstar);

disp('Final dimensional-analysis result:');
disp('delta = Phi * L* =');
pretty(delta_result)
%%
%[text] This is what the code is communicating mathematically:
%[text] - Characteristic length scale: $L^\* = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\nu}{\\omega}}$
%[text] - **Single** $\\Pi$**-group:** $\\Pi = \\frac{\\delta}{L^\*} = \\delta \\sqrt{\\frac{\\omega}{\\nu}}$
%[text] - Since there is only one $\\Pi$-group, the functional relation reduces to a constant: $\\frac{\\delta}{L^\*} = \\Phi = C$
%[text] - Therefore, the Stokes layer thickness scales as: $\\delta = C \\sqrt{\\frac{\\nu}{\\omega}}$ \
%%
%[text] #### 2. Identify the controlling parameter
%[text] \[Note: When the problem asks for the controlling parameter, it is asking:
%[text] - Which dimensionless combination of variables governs the physics of the problem -- i.e., determines the regime and behavior of the flow?\] \
%[text] Let $\\nu = \\mu / \\rho$ be the kinematic viscosity.
%[text] Equivalently,
%[text] $\\delta = C \\sqrt{\\frac{\\nu}{\\omega}}$
%[text] Rewriting the $\\Pi$-group to:
%[text] $\\Pi^2 = \\frac{\\omega \\delta^2}{\\nu}$ $\\leftarrow$ **is the controlling parameter.**
%[text] **One sentence interpretation of what the parameter compares:**
%[text] $\\omega \\delta^2 / \\nu$ compares the oscillation timescale $(1/\\omega)$ to the viscous diffusion timescale across the oscillatory boundary layer $\\delta (\\delta^2 / \\nu)$ - i.e., how far momentum can diffuse in one cycle.
%%
%[text] #### Bonus
%[text] If we retain the plate velocity, then our oscillating boundary layer becomes:
%[text] $\\delta = f(U\_0, \\omega, \\rho, \\mu)$
%[text] - Using the same characteristic length: $L^\* = \\sqrt{(\\nu / \\omega)}$ (the viscous penetration depth per oscillation) \
%[text] $\\Pi$**-group 1: nondimensional thickness**
%[text] $\\Pi\_1 = \\frac{\\delta}{\\sqrt{\\nu/\\omega}}$ $\\leftarrow$ This measures how thick the layer is compared to the viscous diffusion length.
%[text] $\\Pi$**-group 2: nondimensional velocity amplitude**
%[text] We nondimensionalize $U\_0$ using the velocity scale associated with $L^\*$:
%[text] $U^\* \\sim \\frac{L^\*}{T\_{osc}} = \\sqrt{\\nu \\omega}$
%[text] So:
%[text] $\\Pi\_2 = \\frac{U\_0}{\\sqrt{\\nu \\omega}}$ $\\leftarrow$ This is essentially a **Reynolds number** based on the Stokes layer thickness; it measures the oscillation strength.
%[text] - Large $\\Pi\_2$ indicates possible flow seperation, streaming, turbulence. \
%%
%[text] **Buckingham-**$\\Pi$ **form:**
%[text] $\\frac{\\delta}{\\sqrt{\\nu/\\omega}} = \\Phi \\left( \\frac{U\_0}{\\sqrt{\\nu \\omega}} \\right)$
%[text] The velocity amplitude now controls whether the Stokes solution is valid.
%%
%[text] ## Problem 3. Vector calculus warm-up: solid-body rotation
%[text] ### Velocity field visualization
%% HW1 Problem 3 — Solid-body rotation velocity field visualization
% u(x,y,z) = (-Omega*y, Omega*x, 0)

clear; clc; close all;

% --- Parameters you can tweak ---
Omega = 2.0;      % rotation rate (>0)
R     = 1.0;      % reference radius for drawing a circle
L     = 2.5;      % half-width of plotting domain in x,y
N     = 25;       % grid resolution for quiver
Ns    = 20;       % number of streamline seeds

% --- Grid in the plane z = 0 ---
x = linspace(-L, L, N);
y = linspace(-L, L, N);
[X, Y] = meshgrid(x, y);

% Velocity components
U = -Omega .* Y;
V =  Omega .* X;

% Speed (useful for background shading)
Speed = sqrt(U.^2 + V.^2);

%% Figure 1: Quiver + speed background
fig = figure('Color','w'); %[output:2e2db51f]
fig.Theme = "light"; %[output:2e2db51f]
imagesc(x, y, Speed); axis xy equal tight; %[output:2e2db51f]
colorbar; title('Speed |u| with velocity vectors (z=0)'); %[output:2e2db51f]
xlabel('x'); ylabel('y'); hold on; %[output:2e2db51f]

quiver(X, Y, U, V, 'k'); % arrows (MATLAB picks default scaling) %[output:2e2db51f]

% Draw the circle C: x^2 + y^2 = R^2
t = linspace(0, 2*pi, 400);
plot(R*cos(t), R*sin(t), 'w', 'LineWidth', 2); %[output:2e2db51f]
text(0.02*L, 0.90*L, sprintf('\\Omega = %.3g', Omega), 'Color','w', 'FontSize', 12); %[output:2e2db51f]
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_51e5] The vector field represents fluid flow; for each point $(x,y)$ in 2-D space, imagine a particle sitting at $(x,y)$ flowing in the direction of the vector attached to that point, $\\vec{u} (x,y)$. The speed of the particle's movement is determined by the length of that vector \[[4](https://www.khanacademy.org/math/multivariable-calculus/multivariable-derivatives/divergence-and-curl-articles/a/divergence)\].
%[text] Example, State 1 of a flow field:
figure; %[output:993f5a0b]
imshow('flow_field_state1.png'); %[output:993f5a0b]
%[text] State 2 of the flow field:
imshow('flow_field_state2.png'); %[output:5348d8f6]
%[text] During this fluid flow example, some regions become more dense than others, as dots / particles move flow towards those regions.
%[text] For a given vector-valued function, a flow field, the change in **density** **of particles** around a point $(x,y)$ can be measured, as the fluid particles flow along the vectors given by $\\vec{u} (x,y)$, by a variation of the derivative called **divergence**.
%[text] - Note: Divergence outputs a **scalar field**, <u>not</u> a vector field. \
%[text] **Interpretation of divergence**
imshow('divergence_interp.png'); %[output:81ec5113]
%%
%[text] ### 1. Compute the divergence 
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_689f] $\\nabla \\cdot \\vec{u}$
%[text] Is the flow incompressible?
%[text] 
%[text] Let the velocity field be
%[text] $\\vec{u}(x,y,z) = (-\\Omega y,\\; \\Omega x,\\; 0)$ (rigid rotating disk w/angular velocity $\\Omega$, counter-clockwise rotation)
%[text] 
%[text] Define the velocity components
%[text] $\\vec{u} = (u,v,w)$
%[text] 
%[text] where
%[text] $u = -\\Omega y, \\qquad v = \\Omega x, \\qquad w = 0$
%[text] 
%[text] The divergence of a vector field is
%[text] $\\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{u} = \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x} + \\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial y} + \\frac{\\partial w}{\\partial z}$
%[text] 
%[text] Compute each term.
%[text] $\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial x} = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x}(-\\Omega y) = 0$
%[text] (since the expression contains no $x$ dependence)
%[text] $\\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial y} = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y}(\\Omega x) = 0$
%[text] (since the expression contains no $y$ dependence)
%[text] $\\frac{\\partial w}{\\partial z} = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial z}(0) = 0$
%[text] 
%[text] #### Result
%[text] $\\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{u} = 0 + 0 + 0 = 0$
%[text] 
%[text] #### Conclusion
%[text] Since
%[text] $\\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{u} = 0$
%[text] the velocity field is **incompressible.**
%%

%% Figure 2: Streamlines (rotation about +z)
fig = figure('Color','w'); %[output:70bd2e6c]
fig.Theme = "light"; %[output:70bd2e6c]
plot(R*cos(t), R*sin(t), 'k--', 'LineWidth', 1.5); hold on; axis equal; %[output:70bd2e6c]
title('Streamlines of u = (-\Omega y, \Omega x, 0) in the plane z=0'); %[output:70bd2e6c]
xlabel('x'); ylabel('y'); %[output:70bd2e6c]

% Seed points for streamlines (avoid the origin exactly)
rs = linspace(0.2*L, 0.95*L, ceil(Ns/2));
theta = linspace(0, 2*pi, ceil(Ns/2)+1); theta(end) = [];
[RS, TH] = meshgrid(rs, theta);
SX = RS(:).*cos(TH(:));
SY = RS(:).*sin(TH(:));

streamline(X, Y, U, V, SX, SY); %[output:70bd2e6c]
grid on; xlim([-L L]); ylim([-L L]); %[output:70bd2e6c]

%%
%% Figure 3: Optional — show angular direction with a few sample particles
fig = figure('Color','w'); %[output:9d15e818]
fig.Theme = "light"; %[output:9d15e818]
axis equal; grid on; hold on; %[output:9d15e818]
title('Sample particle paths (should be circles)'); xlabel('x'); ylabel('y'); %[output:9d15e818]
xlim([-L L]); ylim([-L L]); %[output:9d15e818]

% Pick a few initial radii and integrate dx/dt = u
r0_list = [0.5*R, R, 1.5*R];
for r0 = r0_list
    % initial point on +x axis
    x0 = r0; y0 = 0;
    f = @(t,xy) [-Omega*xy(2); Omega*xy(1)];
    tspan = [0, 2*pi/Omega]; % one revolution
    [tt, sol] = ode45(f, tspan, [x0; y0]);
    plot(sol(:,1), sol(:,2), 'LineWidth', 1.5); %[output:9d15e818]
end
plot(0,0,'k.','MarkerSize',16); %[output:9d15e818]
legend("r_0=0.5R","r_0=R","r_0=1.5R","Location","best"); %[output:9d15e818]
%%
%[text] ### 3. Circulation, or vortex strength
%[text] 
%[text] 3\.1    The circulation of a velocity field around a closed curve $C$ is defined as
%[text] $\\Gamma = \\oint\_C \\mathbf{u}\\cdot d\\ell$
%[text] 
%[text] For the velocity field
%[text] $\\mathbf{u}(x,y,z) = (-\\Omega y,\\; \\Omega x,\\; 0),$
%[text] and a curve lying in the plane $z=0$, the differential line element is
%[text] $d \\ell = (dx,dy,0)$
%[text] 
%[text] Therefore the integrand becomes
%[text] $\\vec{u} \\cdot d \\ell = (-\\Omega y)dx + (\\Omega x)dy$
%[text] 
%[text] 3\.2    Parametrization of the Circle
%[text] 
%[text] The curve $C$ is the circle
%[text] $x^2 + y^2 = R^2$
%[text] 
%[text] A **circle** is parameterized as (consistent with the counterclockwise orientation)
%[text] $x = R\\cos\\theta, \\qquad y = R\\sin\\theta, \\qquad 0 \\le \\theta \\le 2\\pi$
%[text] - Note: To "stretch" the circle to radius $R$, multiply the parameters by this factor. \
%[text] Differentiating gives
%[text] $dx = -R\\sin\\theta\\, d\\theta, \\qquad dy = R\\cos\\theta\\, d\\theta$
%[text] 
%[text] 3\.3    Substitute into the Circulation Integral
%[text] 
%[text] First term:
%[text] $(-\\Omega y)dx = (-\\Omega R\\sin\\theta)(-R\\sin\\theta\\, d\\theta) = \\Omega R^2 \\sin^2\\theta\\, d\\theta$
%[text] 
%[text] Second term:
%[text] $(\\Omega x)dy = (\\Omega R\\cos\\theta)(R\\cos\\theta\\, d\\theta) = \\Omega R^2 \\cos^2\\theta\\, d\\theta$
%[text] 
%[text] Adding the two terms:
%[text] $\\vec{u} \\cdot d \\ell = \\Omega R^2(\\sin^2\\theta + \\cos^2\\theta)d\\theta$
%[text] 
%[text] Using the identity
%[text] $\\sin^2\\theta + \\cos^2\\theta = 1$
%[text] we obtain
%[text] $\\vec{u} \\cdot d\\ell = \\Omega R^2\\, d\\theta$
%[text] 
%[text] 3\.4    Evaluate the Integral
%[text] 
%[text] \\$
%[text] \\Gamma
%[text] =
%[text] \\int\_0^{2\\pi} \\Omega R^2\\, d\\theta
%[text] =
%[text] \\Omega R^2 (2\\pi).
%[text] \\$\\$
%[text] 
%[text] \\textbf{Final Result}
%[text] 
%[text] \\$\\$
%[text] \\boxed{\\Gamma = 2\\pi \\Omega R^2}
%[text] \\$\\$
%%
%[text] ## References
%[text] \[1\] [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stokes\_problem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stokes_problem)
%[text] \[2\] **S. T. Raml,** ***Oscillatory Flow Mechanism for Enhanced Heat Transfer*** — Master’s thesis demonstrating how oscillating boundary motion can improve convective heat transfer by inducing unsteady boundary–layer motion. 
%[text] \[3\] **Stokes Problem overview (classic fluid dynamics text references)** — Standard fluid mechanics sources (e.g., Batchelor, *An Introduction to Fluid Dynamics*, and Landau & Lifshitz, *Fluid Mechanics*) establish the fundamental oscillatory boundary layer solutions from which damping and drag models are derived.
%[text] \[4\] Divergence, Khan Academy online resource -- [https://www.khanacademy.org/math/multivariable-calculus/multivariable-derivatives/divergence-and-curl-articles/a/divergence](https://www.khanacademy.org/math/multivariable-calculus/multivariable-derivatives/divergence-and-curl-articles/a/divergence) 
%[text] \[5\] Flow integrals and circulation -- [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iXQpDrWrizc](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iXQpDrWrizc) 

